{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17475250","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17475250"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:31:22+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:31:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12585"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12585","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12585"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.06,0.25,0.62,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5081"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109226"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5081","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5081"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12585"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91581"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"40"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"8629"},{"type":"tags","id":"9847"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9001"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10389"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13237"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109226","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109226"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to her General Practice clinic for a routine prenatal checkup during her second trimester of pregnancy. She has been taking indomethacin for rheumatoid arthritis. Her medical history includes rheumatoid arthritis diagnosed five years ago. She takes indomethacin regularly for pain management. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe obstetrician advises her to discontinue indomethacin due to the risk of premature closure of the ductus arteriosus in her baby\u0027s heart. The obstetrician explains fetal circulation, emphasising the importance of ensuring proper circulation for the baby after birth.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is true regarding fetal circulation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Oxygenated blood primarily flows through the fetal pulmonary circulation","Deoxygenated blood flows through the umbilical vein into the fetal liver before reaching the heart","Oxygenated blood flows through the ductus arteriosus, supplying the fetal lungs with oxygen","Oxygenated blood is diverted away from the lungs through the patent foramen ovale","Oxygenated blood is diverted away from the kidneys through the patent foramen ovale"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn fetal circulation, oxygen and nutrients from the mother\u0027s blood cross the placenta to the fetus. Oxygenated blood enters the right atrium, flows through the foramen ovale into the left atrium, passes to the left ventricle, and then enters the aorta. This blood supplies the heart muscle, brain, and arms. Blood returns to the right atrium through the superior vena cava with minimal mixing. Less oxygenated blood enters the right ventricle, then the pulmonary artery. Some goes to the lungs, while most is shunted to the descending aorta via the ductus arteriosus. This blood enters the umbilical arteries and flows to the placenta, where carbon dioxide and waste are released, and oxygen and nutrients enter the fetus\u0027 blood.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOxygenated blood primarily flows through the fetal pulmonary circulation\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. In the fetal circulatory system, the primary goal is to bypass the fetal pulmonary circulation since the lungs are non-functional in utero. Oxygenated blood is primarily directed away from the lungs through shunts like the patent foramen ovale.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDeoxygenated blood flows through the umbilical vein into the fetal liver before reaching the heart\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. Oxygenated blood primarily flows from the umbilical vein directly into the fetal heart, bypassing the fetal liver.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOxygenated blood flows through the ductus arteriosus, supplying the fetal lungs with oxygen\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. The ductus arteriosus allows some blood to bypass the fetal lungs, but it\u0027s not the primary pathway for oxygenated blood in fetal circulation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOxygenated blood is diverted away from the lungs through the patent foramen ovale\u003C/strong\u003E is correct. The patent foramen ovale is a normal fetal cardiac shunt that diverts oxygenated blood away from the non-functional fetal lungs directly into the left atrium, contributing to systemic circulation and bypassing the pulmonary circulation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOxygenated blood is diverted away from the kidneys through the patent foramen ovale\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. The patent foramen ovale diverts oxygenated blood away from the non-functional fetal lungs, not the kidneys.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Fetal circulation directs oxygenated blood away from non-functional lungs through the patent foramen ovale."],"references":["Rudolph AM, Heymann MA. The fetal circulation. Annu Rev Med. 1968;19:195-206. doi: 10.1146/annurev.me.19.020168.001211. PMID: 4871686"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91581"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12585"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91581","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/91581"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-19T15:35:35+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-19T15:35:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5081"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109226"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"40","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/40"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\u2699\ufe0f","name":"Physiology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"4"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember 